message: Start by using scissors on two different 'soft' ingredients (e.g., newspaper, thread, flower, leaf, mushroom, cardboard). Each cut soft item gives 25 points. Once you have two such items (e.g., 'cut thread' and 'cut leaf'), combine them. This consistently yields 80 points (e.g., 'cut thread leaf blend'). When your score is 80 (or generally high, above 60), use the 'frame' tool on this 80-point combined item. This reliably gives 100 points. Avoid using scissors on 'hard' items or on items that are already 'cut' or complex, as this often leads to negative values. Framing is generally very effective when your score is already high.

message: Start by using scissors on all soft ingredients; this reliably yields +25 value per item. The most effective strategy for high scores is combining two 'cut' soft items, which often results in 50-80 points. Once an item reaches a value of 60 or more, framing it can lead to the maximum score of 100. Avoid using scissors on items that are already 'cut' or on hard materials, as this usually results in significant value loss. Combining more than two ingredients, especially if they have mixed features (soft/hard, cut/uncut), tends to create 'overcomplicated' items with negative values.

To get to 80 points, combine a 'cut natural, soft' item with a 'cut artificial, soft' item (e.g., cut leaf + cut paper). Avoid using scissors on hard objects or combining too many items, as these actions often lead to negative values.
